        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-03-18T01:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-03-18T01:00:00-05:00" n="538" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d538">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">501.BB Palestine/3–1849: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Jerusalem</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Burdett</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <gloss target="#t_niact1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">niact</hi>
                        </gloss>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Jerusalem</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-03-18T08:00:00+02:00">March 18, 1949—8 a. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">us urgent</hi>
                </p>
                <p>233. <gloss target="#t_Palun1">Palun</gloss> 88. For Acheson from Ethridge.
                    Technical study entitled “Arab refugee problem” handed me yesterday by Israeli
                    Government largely repeats Sharett’s statement in previous conversations. Study
                    begins with denial of responsibility, minimizes dislocation and in brief can be
                    summed up in one sentence “when the whole matter comes up for discussion in the
                    context of general peace talks the Israeli Government will consider whether
                    conditions are stable enough for a certain number to come back without creating
                    a security problem”. Study emphasizes Israeli viewpoint that resettlement in
                    Arab states is main solution and not repatriation and continues with estimate of
                    abilities of Arab states to absorb them.</p>
                <p>Pouching text.</p>
                <p>Sent Department, repeated Baghdad 17, Damascus 14, Cairo 17, Jidda 8, Amman 18.
                    [Ethridge.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Burdett</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
